# ISSUE-004 spike — restore-rehearsal connections + credentials.
#
# This is an R8 "you-present" spike: it exercises the OPERATOR's REAL Supabase infra and
# backup-ops credentials. Nothing here is committed (.env is gitignored). Fill in what you
# have; main.ts refuses to run and prints exactly what is missing rather than silently
# "passing" with no infra (a #3 silent-failure guard).
#
# Use the DIRECT connection (session mode, port 5432), NOT the transaction pooler
# (port 6543) — same GUC/DDL caveat as ISSUE-002. Restore/assert steps run DDL and read the
# whole restored DB; the transaction pooler can break session-scoped state and prepared
# statements. Supabase → Project Settings → Database → Connection string → "Direct
# connection". It looks like:
#   postgresql://postgres:<PASSWORD>@db.<ref>.supabase.co:5432/postgres


# ── SOURCE (the project whose backup we restore) ─────────────────────────────────────────
# Direct connection to a SOURCE Supabase project holding representative data. If the project
# is EMPTY the harness seeds it (src/seed.ts) so the backup has something meaningful to
# restore: a `memories` table with vector(1536) embeddings + rows, and auth.users rows.
# REQUIRED.
SOURCE_DB_URL=


# ── PATH B target (off-platform pg_dump → pg_restore) ────────────────────────────────────
# Direct connection to a THROWAWAY Supabase project — the path-B restore target. DISPOSABLE:
# create it just for this rehearsal and delete it after (it will receive a full restore of
# the source). This is the path the harness CAN drive end-to-end (pg_dump → pg_restore/psql).
# REQUIRED to exercise path B.
TARGET_DB_URL=


# ── PATH A target (in-project PITR/daily backup, restored OUT-OF-BAND) ────────────────────
# The in-project backup CANNOT be restored from a connection string — it is restored via the
# Supabase dashboard / Management API / PITR into a NEW project (see README "Honesty
# caveats"). If you (the operator) restored the in-project backup into a throwaway project
# out-of-band, paste THAT project's direct connection string here and the harness will run
# the SAME completeness+queryability assertions against it. OPTIONAL (leave blank to skip
# path A; the evidence block records path A as "not exercised" rather than faking it).
TARGET_A_DB_URL=

# If path A was restored out-of-band, record the MEASURED wall-clock restore time (minutes)
# you observed in the dashboard/Management-API restore, so the evidence carries a real path-A
# RTO (AC-NFR-DR.005.1 — measured, not assumed). OPTIONAL; used only when TARGET_A_DB_URL is set.
# TARGET_A_RESTORE_MINUTES=


# ── Management API (optional automation of path A) ───────────────────────────────────────
# A Supabase Management API personal access token + the source project ref, IF you want the
# harness to LIST/trigger the in-project backup for path A programmatically. Note: as of this
# writing the Management API can enumerate backups and trigger a PITR/restore, but the RESTORE
# TARGET is a Supabase-managed operation, not a psql connection — so even with these set, path
# A still lands the restore into a project we then assert against via TARGET_A_DB_URL. OPTIONAL.
# SUPABASE_MGMT_TOKEN=
# SOURCE_PROJECT_REF=


# ── Pre-existing dump artifact (optional) ────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Path to an already-produced off-platform pg_dump artifact (the ADR-008 §2 client-owned
# copy). If set, src/dump.ts uses THIS file instead of generating a fresh dump from SOURCE.
# OPTIONAL. Else the harness runs pg_dump against SOURCE_DB_URL into results/.
# PGDUMP_ARTIFACT=/absolute/path/to/source.dump


# ── Corpus profile overrides (contestable-by-design; see src/config.ts) ──────────────────
# Only used when the harness seeds an empty SOURCE. Defaults give a meaningful restore.
# N_MEMORIES=5000
# N_AUTH_USERS=25
# EMBED_DIM=1536


# ── TOOLING (host, not env) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The harness shells out to `pg_dump` and `pg_restore`/`psql` (path B). You must have the
# Postgres client tools installed and on PATH, matching the server major version (Supabase is
# currently Postgres 15/17 — a newer client is fine, an older one is not). Check with:
#   pg_dump --version && pg_restore --version && psql --version
